{"response":"In modern nations, people frequently die of heart disease and old age, while in earlier times, people frequently died of simple injuries such as being gored by an ox or wounded by machine created during the industrial revolution. Basic injuries used to cause infections which would lead to death. This changed because of penicillin.

Penicillin cures infections very well. It saved 12-15% of soldiers who fought in World War 2. Deaths from infection decreased all over the world.

But germs evolving, and antibiotics are losing their effectiveness. The germs have become so advanced that some companies have given up on trying to cure them. As a result, deaths from infections are starting to increase. Up to 700,000 people are expected to die from infections per year. If trends continue, up to 10 million could die to infections every year.","generation":0,"replication":0,"participant_id":14,"read_multiple_versions":1,"generation_size":40,"num_times_read":3}

{"response":"In the days before the invention of antibiotics, people often died of accidents and the infections that came with them. When Alexander Flemming discovered penicillin, that changed and many more lives were saved, especially during WW2. 

The problem became that we started to use antibiotics with such frequency, that they have become ineffective to combat infections or "superbugs". Each year, scientist go back to the lab to try and tweak the antibiotic to fit the need, but now we are at the end and some bugs are resistant.

In order to lave 10 million lives in 2015, we must reduce the consumption of antibiotics in medicine form as well as food products.","generation":0,"replication":0,"participant_id":19,"read_multiple_versions":1,"generation_size":40,"num_times_read":3}

{"response":"In the past, we humans didn't die of cancer or heart disease; we didn't live long enough to develop those maladies. Instead we died from injuries, accidents on the job, and infections. But that changed in 1928 when Walther Flemming discovered humanities first antibiotic--penicillin. The discovery of penicillin was a game changer in terms of medicine and human lie expectancy. In fact, penicillin is credited for saving as much as 15% of the Allied forces from deadly infections during World War II.

But those golden days of effective antibiotics seems to be coming to an end. Bacteria that have develop resistant to our antibiotics have risen, and their growth had been rapid. Not, we are dealing with infection that only one or two drugs can treat, if any at all. The British government estimated that 700,000 people died of infection each year globally. That can rise to 10 million by 2050 if nothing is done.

The best way to to help slow down the rise of "super bugs" is to curtail our usage of antibiotics.","generation":0,"replication":0,"participant_id":34,"read_multiple_versions":1,"generation_size":40,"num_times_read":3}

{"response":"The number one cause of death wasn't heart disease in the past, it was getting gored by an ox, or being crush by a machine introduced in the industrial revolution. The cause of death from these was usually infection. Previously, an infection knocked out 12-15% of the Allied Forced. But then, penicilin was discovered and infections that would previously be a death sentence we now gone within days.

However, antibiotic overuse has caused bacteria to mutate and become resistant to drugs. Now, more people are dying from infections again because they can't be treated with traditional drugs anymore. Experts estimate that 10 million people will die from antibiotic resistant infections by 2050. 

Do your part by forgoing the antibiotics for your kid's ear infection and doesn't eat meat that has been raised with antibiotics. ","generation":0,"replication":0,"participant_id":82,"read_multiple_versions":1,"generation_size":40,"num_times_read":3}
